\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. D. fisheri} R. Br. in Parry,{\i  Jour. Voy. N.W. Pass., Suppl. App. }291 (1824). Rhizomatous. Stems 10-25(-40) cm, rather stout. Leaves 1-4 mm wide, smooth and glabrous, longitudinally folded; sheaths often purplish; ligule c. 1 mm, truncate. Panicle 2-5(-12) cm; branches erect or sometimes patent or the lower deflexed. Spikelets c. 4 mm, usually with 2 florets. Glumes and lemma purple, with golden hyaline margins. Glumes ovate-lanceolate to ovate, truncate, obtuse. Lemma with long hairs at base and short hairs on the surface, unawned. Stamens c. 2 mm. 2n = 88.{\i  Wet tundra. Svalbard, Arctic Russia.} Rs (N) Sb. ({\i Circumpolar}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. D. psilosantha} (Rupr.) Griseb. in Ledeb.,{\i  Fl. Ross.}{\b  4}: 386 (1852). Like {\b 1} but spikelets 5-8 mm, usually with 1 floret; glumes acuminate; lemma with long hairs at base, otherwise glabrous, usually mucronate or awned; stamens c. 3 mm. 2n = 44.{\i  Wet tundra. Svalbard, Arctic Russia.} Rs (N) Sb. ({\i Circumpolar.})
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   Plants intermediate between {\b 1} and {\b 2} are of fairly frequent occurrence and further work may show that {\b 2} should be regarded as a variety of {\b 1}.
\par

